**Abstract:**
Major essay dated December 3, 1998 titled "On Statements and Statements" with de Lubac quotation on faith and knowledge. Detailed analysis of Searle's Speech Acts theory covering: speech-acts as basic linguistic unit, saying what is meant, illocutionary vs. perlocutionary distinction. Develops extended critique using "hammer in next room" and "mother on phone" examples. Argues all speech-acts are performative and that Searle's model is based on written/read language rather than spoken interaction.

